<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[118, 73, 920, 125]]<|/det|>
Two particles \(P\) and \(Q\), of masses \(m \mathrm{kg}\) and \(0.3 \mathrm{kg}\) respectively, are at rest on a smooth horizontal plane. \(P\) is projected at a speed of \(5 \mathrm{m s}^{-1}\) directly towards \(Q\). After \(P\) and \(Q\) collide, \(P\) moves with a speed of \(2 \mathrm{m s}^{-1}\) in the same direction as it was originally moving.

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[118, 137, 146, 155]]<|/det|>
<label>(a)</label>

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[158, 136, 588, 155]]<|/det|>
Find, in terms of \(m\), the speed of \(Q\) after the collision.

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[890, 137, 920, 155]]<|/det|>
<mark>[2]

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[158, 510, 920, 545]]<|/det|>
After this collision, \(Q\) moves directly towards a third particle \(R\), of mass \(0.6 \mathrm{kg}\), which is at rest on the plane. \(Q\) is brought to rest in the collision with \(R\), and \(R\) begins to move with a speed of \(1.5 \mathrm{m s}^{-1}\).

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[116, 559, 148, 576]]<|/det|>
<label>(b)</label>

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[156, 559, 321, 576]]<|/det|>
Find the value of \(m\).

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[890, 559, 920, 576]]<|/det|>
<mark>[2]

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[76, 74, 97, 92]]<|/det|>
<label>2</label>

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[118, 72, 920, 92]]<|/det|>
A particle \(P\) of mass \(0.4 \mathrm{kg}\) is projected vertically upwards from horizontal ground with speed \(10 \mathrm{m s}^{-1}\).

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[116, 104, 146, 123]]<|/det|>
<label>(a)</label>

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[156, 103, 603, 123]]<|/det|>
Find the greatest height above the ground reached by \(P\).

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[890, 103, 920, 123]]<|/det|>
<mark>[2]

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[111, 380, 920, 415]]<|/det|>
When \(P\) reaches the ground again, it bounces vertically upwards. At the first instant that it hits the ground, \(P\) loses \(7.2 \text{J}\) of energy.

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[116, 426, 146, 444]]<|/det|>
<label>(b)</label>

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[156, 425, 781, 444]]<|/det|>
Find the time between the first and second instants at which \(P\) hits the ground.

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[890, 425, 920, 444]]<|/det|>
<mark>[4]

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[77, 75, 94, 92]]<|/det|>
<label>3</label>

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[118, 74, 920, 109]]<|/det|>
A particle moves in a straight line starting from rest. The displacement \(s\) m of the particle from a fixed point \(O\) on the line at time \(t\) s is given by

<|ref|>equation<|/ref|><|det|>[[430, 115, 569, 139]]<|/det|>
\[s = t^{\frac{5}{2}} - \frac{15}{4} t^{\frac{3}{2}} + 6.\]

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[118, 148, 536, 167]]<|/det|>
Find the value of \(s\) when the particle is again at rest.

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[890, 148, 920, 166]]<|/det|>
<mark>[4]

Four coplanar forces act at a point. The magnitudes of the forces are \(F\mathrm{N}\), \(10\mathrm{N}\), \(50\mathrm{N}\) and \(40\mathrm{N}\). The directions of the forces are as shown in the diagram.

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[116, 448, 146, 467]]<|/det|>
<label>(a)</label>

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[156, 448, 781, 467]]<|/det|>

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[118, 287, 920, 370]]<|/det|>
Two particles \(P\) and \(Q\), of masses \(0.2\mathrm{kg}\) and \(0.1\mathrm{kg}\) respectively, are attached to the ends of a light inextensible string. The string passes over a fixed smooth pulley at \(B\) which is attached to two inclined planes. Particle \(P\) lies on a smooth plane \(AB\) which is inclined at \(60^{\circ}\) to the horizontal. Particle \(Q\) lies on a plane \(BC\) which is inclined at an angle of \(\theta^{\circ}\) to the horizontal. The string is taut and the particles can move on lines of greatest slope of the two planes (see diagram).

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[116, 381, 146, 399]]<|/det|>
<label>(a)</label>

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[156, 381, 920, 415]]<|/det|>
It is given that \(\theta = 60\), the plane \(BC\) is rough and the coefficient of friction between \(Q\) and the plane \(BC\) is 0.7. The particles are released from rest.

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[156, 427, 468, 445]]<|/det|>
Determine whether the particles move.

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[890, 428, 920, 445]]<|/det|>
<mark>[4]

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[116, 73, 148, 91]]<|/det|>
<label>(b)</label>

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[156, 73, 920, 108]]<|/det|>
It is given instead that the plane \(BC\) is smooth. The particles are released from rest and in the subsequent motion the tension in the string is \(\left(\sqrt{3} - 1\right)\mathrm{N}\).

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[156, 120, 920, 138]]<|/det|>
Find the magnitude of the acceleration of \(P\) as it moves on the plane, and find the value of \(\theta\). [4]

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[76, 73, 94, 92]]<|/det|>
